rDNA promoter, e.g. TIF-IB/SL1 and UBF, or are assembled into productive
transcription initiation complexes via interaction with Pol I, e.g.
TIF-IA, and TIF-IC. Here we show that all components required for
specific rDNA transcription initiation are capable of physical interaction
with Pol I in the absence of DNA and can be co-immunoprecipitated
with antibodies against defined subunits of murine Pol I. Sucrose
gradient centrifugation and fractionation on gel filtration columns
reveals that approximately 10\% of cellular Pol I elutes as a defined
complex with an apparent molecular mass of > 2000 kDa. The large
Pol I complex contains saturating levels of TIF-IA, TIF-IB and UBF,
but limiting amounts of TIF-IC. In support of the existence of a
functional complex between Pol I and basal factors, the large complex
is transcriptionally active after complementation with TIF-IC. The
