affinities for the different types of lesions, the presence of large
amounts of competitor DNA or the need for glutaraldehyde fixation
prevented the quantification of equilibrium constants. We have performed
a quantitative study on the binding of XPC to damaged DNA using fluorescence
anisotropy measurements. The XPC-HR23B complex binds with high affinity
(K(D) approximately 1-3 nM) to fluorescent 36 bp DNA fragments containing
a single cisplatin 1,3-intrastrand adduct or a six-nucleotide mispaired
region. From stoichiometric titration experiments, it is concluded
that approximately 70\% of the XPC-HR23B preparation is active in
DNA binding. Binding experiments employing fluorescent probes with
a single defined photoproduct reveal a 30-fold preference of XPC
for 6,4-photoproducts as compared to a cyclobutane dimer. Competition
