dynamics of RNA polymerase I (RNA Pol I) assembly and transcriptional
output. We show that transcriptional upregulation is accompanied
by prolonged retention of RNA Pol I components at the promoter, resulting
in longer promoter dwell time, and an increase in the steady-state
population of assembling polymerase. As a consequence, polymerase
assembly efficiency and, ultimately, the rate of entry into processive
elongation are elevated. Our results show that regulation of rDNA
transcription in vivo occurs via modulation of the efficiency of
transcription complex subunit capture and assembly.},
