partner. Normal repair proficiency was retained when XPA mutations
abolished only the simple interaction with linear DNA molecules.
By contrast, results from a K141E K179E double mutant revealed that
excision is crucially dependent on the assembly of XPA protein with
a sharp bending angle in the DNA substrate. These findings show how
an increased deformability of damaged sites, leading to helical kinks
recognized by XPA, contributes to target selectivity in DNA repair.},
